But let me describe the technique to start with. In 
a few places, the ocean bottom is continuously

10:03.555 --> 10:19.137
building up, as you know, and continuously moving 
and doing all these things that we've begun to

10:03.555 --> 10:19.137
understand from seafloor spreading and 
continental drift. But in a few places around the

10:19.157 --> 10:26.046
world, the bottom waters in Usually in near shore 
basins are anaerobic or anoxic. They have no

10:30.734 --> 10:31.515
oxygen. And nothing lives there. Even though over 
most of the ocean, the sediments are raining down

10:34.078 --> 10:40.105
every year. There are things living there that mix 
them up. And so the time resolution that you can get

10:43.028 --> 10:48.675
is of the order of 10,000 years at the best. The 
sediments are mixed continuously. But in these

10:52.732 --> 10:56.856
regions, they're laid down in layers that you can 
identify year by year. You can put your finger on it

10:57.677 --> 11:02.822
and say, within a few years, that year is the year 
zero right there. That's what the sediments were

11:02.902 --> 11:08.148
laid down in the year zero. As you go back in time, it 
becomes somewhat less certain. But you can just

11:10.150 --> 11:11.151
count back. And you can check your count with 
radioactive dating.

11:17.242 --> 11:27.793
