formation, and you can split it open and you can see

11:17.242 --> 11:27.793
peppered with fish scales and other kinds of 
debris, diatoms, foraminifera. So you know

11:28.734 --> 11:40.887
something in that year of what the Pacific was 
doing, or what the ocean was doing, and something

11:28.734 --> 11:40.887
about what fish were present, you see. Because you 
can identify these scales. You can date these

11:43.387 --> 11:44.489
scales. You can tell how old they were and how fast 
they were growing. You know what species it was.

11:49.256 --> 11:51.980
You know how old the fish was and how fast it had 
grown. So you know a great deal. And you know it for

11:53.442 --> 11:57.488
that year, exactly. Well, the kind of Rosetta 
Stone in this whole business is, of course, if you

11:57.508 --> 12:04.599
try this, how well does this agree to the known 
history? And when we went through that exercise,

12:06.181 --> 12:10.688
we found it agreed very well with the known 
history. where we really know what the

12:11.309 --> 12:33.300
populations of the pelagic fish are out here, our 
results from looking at these sediments and

12:11.309 --> 12:33.300
analyzing the number of scales per year coming 
down, totally independently, gives us the same

12:11.309 --> 12:33.300
curve of the variation between the number of hake, 
the number of anchovies, the number of saris, and

12:11.309 --> 12:33.300
the number of sardines. This gives us confidence 
we can make these same kind of counts back into the

12:34.175 --> 12:42.126
past, as far as we want, and see what has been the 
